'''Baron Eberhardt Otto George von Bock''' (died 21 January 1814) was a Hanoverian born major-general in the [[British army]] during the [[Napoleonic Wars]].

==Biography==
Bock was descended from an old military family, and entered the [[Hanover]]ian cavalry about the year 1781. His name appears as a premier-lieutenant in the 6th Hanoverian dragoons in 1789, and as rittmeister (captain) in 1800.{{sfn|Chichester|1886|p=287}} He served in the Hanoverian Garde du Corps under [[Heinrich Wilhelm von Freytag|Freytag]] in the [[Flanders Campaign]] and was slightly wounded by two sabre cuts on the arm and head at the [[Battle of Famars]] 23 May 1793.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}

On the dissolution of the [[House of Hanover|Hanoverian]] army after the convention of Lauenburg, Bock was one of the officers who travelled to England, where he raised four troops of heavy cavalry, designated as the 1st dragoons, [[King's German Legion]], and was gazetted colonel 21 April 1804. The regiment was formed at Weymouth, and was a particular favourite of George III. Bock served at its head in [[William Cathcart, 1st Earl Cathcart|Lord Cathcart]]'s [[expedition to Hanover]] in 1805; also in Ireland, whither it was sent after its return home. From Ireland Bock, who had attained the rank of major-general in 1810, proceeded to the [[Peninsular War]] in 1811 in command of a brigade composed of the two heavy cavalry regiments of the Legion, with which he made the subsequent campaigns in Spain and the south of France in 1812-13. The steadiness and gallantry of Bock's heavy Germans often won approval, particularly on 23 July 1812, the day after the victory at [[battle of Salamanca|Salamanca]], when in a charge at [[Battle of Garcia Hernandez|Garcia Hernandez]], they attacked, broke and made prisoner three battalions of French infantry formed in square,{{sfn|Chichester|1886|p=287}} usually thought of as a formation impregnable to cavalry. 

Bock was made temporary commander of [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Wellington]]'s Cavalry during [[Stapleton Cotton, 1st Viscount Combermere|Cotton]]'s convalescence July–October 1812, and again December 1812-June 1813. He served in the rearguard during the retreat from [[Siege of Burgos|Burgos]] 1812, mishandling an ambush at [[Battle of Venta del Pozo|Venta del Pozo]] (Villadrigo) 23 October. In 1813 he served at [[battle of Vitoria|Vitoria]] 21 June.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}

Bock suffered from being very short sighted - before the charge at Garcia Hernandez he had to ask to be pointed in the direction of the enemy.{{sfn|Haythornthwaite|p=54}} 

On 21 January 1814, Bock was drowned together with his son Lewis and other officers when the transport ship ''Bellona'' was wrecked on the Tulbest rocks, en route to England. His body was washed on shore at the little Breton village of [[Pleubian]] and interred.{{sfn|Chichester|1886|p=287}}

